@startuml
' cyclic and interval concept diagram for xer

title xer cyclic and interval concepts

skinparam backgroundColor white
skinparam shadowing false
skinparam defaultFontName Monospaced
skinparam defaultTextAlignment center
skinparam rectangle {
  BackgroundColor #FFFDE7
  BorderColor #444444
  RoundCorner 8
}
skinparam note {
  BackgroundColor #F5F5F5
  BorderColor #777777
}
skinparam arrow {
  Color #AA0055
  Thickness 1
}
skinparam usecase {
  BackgroundColor #E8F5E9
  BorderColor #444444
}
left to right direction

rectangle "interval<T>\nbounded linear value" as Interval {
  rectangle "lower bound" as IMin
  rectangle "stored value\nclamped or constrained" as IValue
  rectangle "upper bound" as IMax

  IMin --> IValue : range
  IValue --> IMax : range
}

note bottom of Interval
Typical model:
a value lives inside a finite
linear interval such as [0, 1].

Examples:
- normalized color component
- clamped scalar value
end note

rectangle "cyclic<T>\nwrapped circular value" as Cyclic {
  usecase "0" as C0
  usecase "1/4" as C1
  usecase "1/2" as C2
  usecase "3/4" as C3

  C0 -right- C1
  C1 -down- C2
  C2 -left- C3
  C3 -up- C0
}

note bottom of Cyclic
Typical model:
values wrap around a cycle.

In xer, one full turn is represented
as 1.0, and angle helpers convert
between radian / degree / turn-like
cyclic values.
end note

rectangle "Linear arithmetic" as LinearOps
rectangle "Circular arithmetic" as CircularOps

Interval --> LinearOps : saturate / constrain\ninside bounds
Cyclic --> CircularOps : normalize / wrap\nmodulo one full turn

rectangle "Use in other facilities" as Uses
Interval --> Uses : color components\nbasic_rgb<T>::r/g/b\nbasic_gray<T>::y
Cyclic --> Uses : hue\nbasic_hsv<T>::h\nangle-like quantities

legend bottom
|= Type |= Concept |= Behavior |
| interval<T> | bounded line segment | keeps value inside lower and upper bounds |
| cyclic<T> | circular domain | wraps values around a repeated cycle |
endlegend

@enduml
